name: We Wish You a Merry Christmas
comments: Folk carol from the West Country of England. Possibly from the 16th century. Arthur Warrell (1883-1939) is responsible for the popularity of the carol. Warrell, a lecturer at the University of Bristol from 1909, arranged the tune for his own University of Bristol Madrigal Singers as an elaborate four-part arrangement, which he performed with them in concert on December 6, 1935. His composition was published by Oxford University Press the same year under the title "A Merry Christmas: West Country traditional song".

name: Souvenirs
comments: In 1927 songwriter Edgar Leslie traveled to London, England, were he began a successful collaboration with composer Horatio Nicholls (a pseudonym for music publisher Lawrence Wright). The pair would produce - among others - a song entitled “Among My Souvenirs”, which was published  that same year by the composer's publising company named 'Lawrence Wright Music Co. London'. In the UK the song was originally titled just "Souvenirs", but as soon as the song became known in the USA, it was re-titled "Among My Souvenirs" there.

name: D' Natural Blues
comments: Many sources trace the origin of this work back to the riff from Charlie Parker's Now's the Time . Paul Williams heard Lucky Millinder and His Orchestra perform "D' Natural Blues" and decided to perform this song too. He called it "The Huckle-Buck". The reactions turned out to be very positive and he decided to record it. Lucky Millinder recorded it a few weeks later (in the beginning of January 1949), but it was his band's song and he performed it first.

name: Kokomo Blues
comments: Many people claimed to have written the song, and gave different interpretations about the meaning of the word "Kokomo". In his version, Scrapper Blackwell referenced the town of Kokomo, Indiana, while James Arnold stated that "Koko" was a brand name of coffee sold in "The Eleven Light City", a drugstore in Chicago.

It was copyrighted and originally released as "Yardbird Suite", without the lyrics, which have, however, been recorded occasionally.
